```java
public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        while (n > 1) {
            if (n % 3 != 0) {
                return false;
            }
            n /= 3;
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```

This solution uses a while loop to continuously divide n by 3 as long as it is greater than 1. If at any point n is not divisible by 3, it is not a power of three and we return false. If we reach the end of the loop with n equal to 1, we have confirmed that n is a power of three and we return true.

This solution has a time complexity of O(log n) and a space complexity of O(1), as it does not use any extra data structures that grow with the input size.

The follow-up question asks for a solution without loops or recursion. Here is one possible solution using logarithm:

```java
public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        int log = (int)(Math.log(n) / Math.log(3));
        return n == Math.pow(3, log);
    }
}
```

This solution uses the logarithm function to calculate the exponent x for 3^x that equals n. If the calculated exponent is an integer and n equals 3 raised to that exponent, we can confirm that n is a power of three and return true. Otherwise, we return false. This solution has a time complexity of O(1) and a space complexity of O(1), as it does not use any extra data structures that grow with the input size.

